'''''Alchornea cordifolia''''' is a shrub or small [[tree]] distributed throughout tropical [[Africa]].  The plant is used in traditional African medicine.{{cn|date=March 2015}}

==Chemical constituents ==

The leaves, roots and stem bark contain [[terpenoid]]s, [[steroid glycoside]]s, [[flavonoid]]s, [[tannin]]s, [[saponin]]s, [[carbohydrate]]s and the [[imidazopyrimidine]] [[alkaloid]]s [[alchorneine]], [[alchornidine]], and several [[guanidine]] alkaloids. The leaves also contain a range of [[hydroxybenzoic acid]]s: [[gallic acid]] and its ethyl ester, [[gentisic acid]], [[anthranilic acid]], [[protocatechuic acid]], and [[ellagic acid]] (alizarine yellow). A C20 [[Homology (chemistry)|homolog]] of [[vernolic acid]] named [[alchornoic acid]] can be found in the seed oil.<ref>[http://database.prota.org/PROTAhtml/Alchornea%20cordifolia_En.htm prota.org]</ref>{{dead link|date=April 2016}}

