:''This article is about ipil (Intsia bijuga), for the ipil-ipil tree, see [[Leucaena leucocephala]].''

'''''Intsia bijuga''''' (commonly known as '''Borneo teak''', '''Johnstone River teak''', '''Moluccan ironwood''', '''Pacific teak''' and '''scrub mahogany'''<ref name="GRIN">{{cite web |url=http://www.ars-grin.gov/cgi-bin/npgs/html/taxon.pl?20110 |title=''Intsia bijuga'' (Colebr.) Kuntze |work=Germplasm Resources Information Network |publisher=United States Department of Agriculture |date=2001-10-18 |accessdate=2010-03-26}}</ref>) is a species of [[Flowering plant|flowering]] [[tree]] in the [[pea]] family, [[Fabaceae]], native to the [[Indo-Pacific]]. It ranges from [[Tanzania]] and [[Madagascar]] east through [[India]] and [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] to the [[Pacific Islands|Pacific islands]] of [[Fiji]] and [[Samoa]].<ref name="GRIN"/> It grows to around 50 metres (160 feet) tall with a highly [[Buttress root|buttressed]] trunk. It inhabits [[mangrove]] forests.

The tree has a variety of common names including '''ipil''', '''merbau''' and '''kwila'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unep-wcmc.org/trees/trade/int_bij.htm|title=Tree Conservation Information Service|date=2007-09-05|publisher=UNEP-WCMC|accessdate=2008-08-23}}</ref>  In the [[Philippines]], it also known in some areas as '''taal'''.<ref name=JETE>{{Cite-JETE|Ipil, taal}}</ref>

==Uses==
The bark and leaves of the ipil are used in traditional medicines. The tree's timber, called ''merbau'' or ''kwila'', is a very durable and [[termite]]-resistant wood, making it a highly valued material for flooring and other uses.  The wood can also be used to extract a dye.   Merbau can contain a "gold" fleck that runs through the grain, considered to be attractive by some.
Due to extensive logging of the tree, it is endangered in many places in Southeast Asia, and almost extinct in some.<ref>[http://www.wildsingapore.com/chekjawa/text/f106.htm Wild Singapore]</ref> Extensive amounts were purchased for the venue of the [[2008 Summer Olympics]] in China, which is the largest importer of the wood.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6277518.stm|title=China trade threatens tropical trees|last=Bristow |first=Michael |date=2007-07-06|publisher=BBC}}</ref> The wood is used for flooring in U.S. and European markets where it is commonly sold under different names.  Both licensed and unlicensed mills harvest the wood.

==Illegal logging==
According to [[Greenpeace]] large amounts of ipil timber sourced from [[illegal logging]] is being imported into [[China]] where there are lax import rules. Greenpeace are targeting users in Western countries in order to halt the trade in ipil wood. Greenpeace claims that at the current rate of logging the tree will be wiped out within 35 years.<ref name=BBC/>

In [[New Zealand]], where the ipil wood is known as kwila, attempts have been made to stop it from being imported. In 2008 retailers were divided in whether the sale of kwila should be banned. [[Jim Anderton]], who was the [[Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry (New Zealand)|Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry]] at that time, did not support a ban and instead he left it up to consumer choice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/environment/news/article.cfm?c_id=39&objectid=10527536|title=Stores divided over calls to ban kwila|last=Gibson|first=Eloise|date=18 August 2008|work=New Zealand Herald|accessdate=26 June 2010}}</ref>

==Symbolism==
''Intsia bijuga'', locally known as ''ifit'', is the official tree of the [[United States territory]] of [[Guam]].

